   value_data	: "classic - local users authenticate as themselves"
  </custom_item>

  # Addition over Legacy Benchmark, 3.2.1.50

  # 3.2.1.50 Network Security: Do not store LAN Manager password hash value on next password change: Enabled

  <custom_item>
   type			: REGISTRY_SETTING
   description	: "3.2.1.50 Network Security: Do not store LAN Manager password hash value on next password change: Enabled"
   info			: "The SAM database typically stores a LANManager, or LM,  hash of account passwords. The SAM database should be secure on the workstation; but in the even that it is captured, the LM hash can be retrieved.  Many vulnerabilities exist with the LM authentication model, and brute force attacks usually succeed with ease.  Removing the LM hash from the SAM database will help protect the local account passwords."
   solution		:  "Make sure Network Security: Do not store LAN Manager password hash value on next password change is enabled."
   reference	: "PCI|8.4,800-53|AC-3,800-53|SC-5,CCE|CCE-3632-7,800-53|CM-7,800-53|CM-6"
   see_also		: "https://benchmarks.cisecurity.org/tools2/windows/CIS_Win2003_MS_Benchmark_v2.0.pdf"
   reg_type		: REG_DWORD
   value_type	: POLICY_SET
   reg_key		: "HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa"
   reg_item		: "NoLMHash"
   value_data	: "Enabled"
  </custom_item>

  # Changed from Enterprise Benchmark, 3.2.1.52

  # 3.2.1.52 Network Security: LAN Manager Authentication Level: Send NTLMv2, refuse LM and NTLM

  <custom_item>
   type			: REGISTRY_SETTING
   description	: "3.2.1.52 Network Security: LAN Manager Authentication Level: Send NTLMv2, refuse LM and NTLM"
   info			: "Windows network authentication has changed considerably as various security vulnerabilities have been identified and fixed. The original LAN Manager (or LM) password hash is considered very weak, but is still used by most Windows 9x clients. Using commercially available software, and off-the-shelf computers, most LM password hashes can be used to reveal the actual password in a matter of days, or hours. After NTLM was released it was found to be not much more secure than its previous version thus NTLMv2 was released. NTLMv2 has significant security improvements to its previous version when combined with a strong password policy. Accounts will be much more secure from brute force attacks."
   solution		: "Make sure Network Security: LAN Manager Authentication Level is set to send NTLMv2 and refuse LM and NTLM."
   reference	: "PCI|8.4,800-53|AC-3,800-53|SC-5,800-53|CM-7,CCE|CCE-3703-6,800-53|CM-6"
   see_also		: "https://benchmarks.cisecurity.org/tools2/windows/CIS_Win2003_MS_Benchmark_v2.0.pdf"
   reg_type		: REG_DWORD
   value_type	: LANMAN_SET
   reg_key		: "HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa"
   reg_item		: "lmcompatibilitylevel"
   value_data	: "send ntlmv2 response only\refuse lm & ntlm"
  </custom_item>

  # 3.2.1.53 Network Security: LDAP client signing requirements: Negotiate Signing or Require Signing
  #
  # 0 - None
  # 1 - Negotiate Signing
  # 2 - Require Signing
  #

  <custom_item>
   type			: REGISTRY_SETTING
   description	: "3.2.1.53 Network Security: LDAP client signing requirements: Negotiate Signing or Require Signing"
   info			: "Similar to the SMB protocol, the LDAP protocol supports signing. LDAP, 'Lightweight Directory Access Protocol,' provides one means for the client to talk to active directory. LDAP protocol is text-based, but supports authentication to gain access to sensitive sections of the directory. Require signing to provide the assurance of mutual authentication for this communications channel."
